awd_titl_txt: NNA: Collaborative Research: Navigating the New Arctic; Advanced Technology for Persistent, Long-Range, Autonomous Under-Ice Observation
awd_abstract_narration:
This project advances the national health, prosperity, and welfare by developing and demonstrating a new robotic technology for persistent, autonomous observation of under-ice marine environments over large (>1000 km) spatial scales. The Arctic is undergoing rapid change, with dramatic shifts in the sea ice cover and upper ocean. Monitoring and understanding these changes is critical to improving our ability to predict ongoing change and variability on seasonal to decadal timescales. Current observational capabilities are severely hampered by the logistical challenges of operating in this environment - observations are sparse, infrequent, and expensive to obtain, especially for the under sea ice observations. As a low-cost, easy to deploy platform, the unmanned underwater vehicle developed by this project will be transformative in our capability for effective widespread and continuous monitoring of the Arctic Ocean and its ice cover. Under-ice missions to monitor ice-ocean properties across a retreating ice edge in spring will provide a proof of concept for a unique capability to efficiently address a wide range of scientific questions under the Arctic ice cover that can benefit from measurements over large spatial and temporal scales. This project supports the NSF Big Idea on Navigating the New Arctic. As a future component of an Arctic Observing Network, this innovative technology can provide a critical cog in our ability to effectively monitor the Arctic and inform management of increased Arctic commercial, mineral extraction, and fisheries activities, as well as planning for resilience of Arctic coastal communities.

This project will develop and demonstrate a highly modified autonomous underwater glider (AUG) equipped with a dual-use active sonar for characterizing ice thickness distribution, as well as for real-time terrain-aided navigation. This will enable under-ice observation across extended distances without the need for external navigation aids such as acoustic beacons. The AUG will also encompass an automated mission planner/replanner wherein the vehicle can autonomously adapt its mission plan in response to evolving mission goals and environmental or vehicle state changes, such as data-driven adaptive sampling, changing surfacing locations based on ice drift, or in the event of a component failure impeding vehicle progress and decreasing expected range. Finally, a new variable thrust hybrid propulsion system will be developed for operation in both shallow coastal waters with high currents and deeper waters, enabling efficient transit from coastal to remote science locations, while enabling the vehicle to conduct water column profiling, as well as close-range ice survey. These characteristics will facilitate long-term unattended under-ice observation with reduced cost and logistical requirements.

This award reflects NSF's statutory mission and has been deemed worthy of support through evaluation using the Foundation's intellectual merit and broader impacts review criteria.

por.por_cntn:
Changes in Arctic sea ice dynamics are altering climate, weather, and ecosystems on scales that will profoundly impact indigenous cultures, national economies, and geopolitical security.  Despite the importance of understanding these ice dynamics, most direct observations are still made from icebreakers or drifting ice camps. These methods are extremely expensive, infrequent, and typically short in duration. This research has focused on the development and demonstration of a new type of robotic platform, an autonomous underwater glider (AUG), that enables long-range under-ice survey of the marginal ice zone.

The robot’s low power, embedded intelligence, and minimal logistics requirements allows scaling up for increased coverage while enabling new modes of observation that are infeasible with conventional technologies. This includes long-term unattended observation of seasonal ice advance and retreat dynamics, as well as energy flux (heat and momentum transfer) at basin scales for durations of weeks-to-months. Proof-of-concept demonstrations were successfully completed in the Beaufort Sea in 2023. During these operations the AUG conducted multi-kilometer surveys of the marginal ice zone, synoptically mapping non-stationary ice floes (keel depth, size extent, and distribution), surface wave energy, water currents, acoustic sound channels, and salinity and temperature profiles while submerged. These autonomous observations were georeferenced to within tens of meters, despite the AUG operating without the benefit of external beacons or a true-north seeking inertial navigation system. The vehicle platform's measured transport cost was less than 30 J/m, while surveying at speeds of approximately 1 m/s. This extreme energy efficiency enables it to transit distances of up to 14,000 km when in low power mode, and conduct survey operations of up to 1,500km on a single charge. Unlike conventional AUGs, this system’s high-efficiency lifting surfaces and hybrid propulsion system enables it to operate equally well within shallow ice-covered coastal regions and deep open ocean environments, thereby allowing shore launch/recovery and potentially eliminating the need for surface vessel support.

Results from these preliminary Arctic operations have provided new insight into seasonal ice retreat in the Beaufort Sea, revealing localized density stratifications that develop from melting ice, which are periodically mixed away by storm events. This process is characterized by the persistence of large ice floes that appear to be remnants of pressure ridges. Observations indicate that these large floes can become grounded at water depths to 35m, and act as dams to ice floe and water column movement until sufficient heat or momentum (i.e. winds, waves, and currents) trigger breakup with an accompanied acute mixing event. These dynamics have profound implications for marine ecosystems and built infrastructure, particularly among indigenous populations centers along the Arctic coast.   

This method of unattended robotic survey is directly transferable to other polar regions, including for study under Greenland and Antarctic ice shelves, and for validating satellite altimetry estimates of ice coverage and thickness. The AUG’s extended range, improved navigation, and sonar payload systems are broadly useful for a wide range of scientific investigation and, due to the extremely low unit hardware costs, can be scaled up for use in NSF’s Ocean Observatory Initiative. The technology may also increase scientific understanding of other transient phenomena impacting coastal and shelf margins, including large storm events such as hurricanes, or observation of transient ocean surface phenomena such as Sargasso blooms.
